ainstorming skill\" [shape=box];\n    \"Might any skill apply?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"Invoke Skill tool\" [shape=box];\n    \"Announce: 'Using [skill] to [purpose]'\" [shape=box];\n    \"Has checklist?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"Create TodoWrite todo per item\" [shape=box];\n    \"Follow skill exactly\" [shape=box];\n    \"Respond (including clarifications)\" [shape=doublecircle];\n\n    \"About to EnterPlanMode?\" -> \"Already brainstormed?\";\n    \"Already brainstormed?\" -> \"Invoke brainstorming skill\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Already brainstormed?\" -> \"Might any skill apply?\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Invoke brainstorming skill\" -> \"Might any skill apply?\";\n\n    \"User message received\" -> \"Might any skill apply?\";\n    \"Might any skill apply?\" -> \"Invoke Skill tool\" [label=\"yes, even 1%\"];\n    \"Might any skill apply?\" -> \"Respond (including clarifications)\" [label=\"definitely not\"];\n    \"Invoke Skill tool\" -> \"Announce: 'Using [skill] to [purpose]'\";\n    \"Announce: 'Using [skill] to [purpose]'\" -> \"Has checklist?\";\n    \"Has checklist?\" -> \"Create TodoWrite todo per item\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Has checklist?\" -> \"Follow skill exactly\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Create TodoWrite todo per item\" -> \"Follow skill exactly\";\n}\n```\n\n## Red Flags\n\nThese thoughts mean STOP—you're rationalizing:\n\n| Thought | Reality |\n|---------|---------|\n| \"This is just a simple question\" | Questions are tasks. Check for skills. |\n| \"I need more context first\" | Skill check comes BEFORE clarifying questions. |\n| \"Let me explore the codebase first\" | Skills tell you HOW to explore. Check first. |\n| \"I can check git/files quickly\" | Files lack conversation context. Check for skills. |\n| \"Let me gather information first\" | Skills tell you HOW to gather information. |\n| \"This doesn't need a formal skill\" | If a skill exists, use it. |\n| \"I remember this skill\" | Skills evolve. Read current version. |\n| \"This doesn't count as a task\" | Action = task. Check for skills. |\n| \"The skill is overkill\" | Simple things become complex. Use it. |\n| \"I'll just do this one thing first\" | Check BEFORE doing anything. |\n| \"This feels productive\" | Undisciplined action wastes time. Skills prevent this. |\n| \"I know what that means\" | Knowing the concept ≠ using the skill. Invoke it. |\n\n## Skill Priority\n\nWhen multiple skills could apply, use this order:\n\n1. **Process skills first** (brainstorming, debugging) - these determine HOW to approach the task\n2. **Implementation skills second** (frontend-design, mcp-builder) - these guide execution\n\n\"Let's build X\" → brainstorming first, then implementation skills.\n\"Fix this bug\" → debugging first, then domain-specific skills.\n\n## Skill Types\n\n**Rigid** (TDD, debugging): Follow exactly. Don't adapt away discipline.\n\n**Flexible** (patterns): Adapt principles to context.\n\nThe skill itself tells you which.\n\n## User Instructions\n\nInstructions say WHAT, not HOW. \"Add X\" or \"Fix Y\" doesn't mean skip workflows.\n","exit_code":0,"duration":{"secs":0,"nanos":3375},"formatted_output":"","status":"completed"}}
{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T22:57:03.983Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"exec_command_end","call_id":"call_umWNuF1jlCRs8nMgckbxbrk4","process_id":"52079","turn_id":"019ddb75-b2a6-7d60-820d-1e9a515a4cbe","command":["/bin/zsh","-lc","sed -n '1,260p' /Users/alisha/.agents/skills/marvin/SKILL.md"],"cwd":"/Users/alisha/.marvin/worktrees/project-overview","parsed_cmd":[{"type":"read","cmd":"sed -n '1,260p' /Users/alisha/.agents/skills/marvin/SKILL.md","name":"SKILL.md","path":"/Users/alisha/.agents/skills/marvin/SKILL.md"}],"source":"unified_exec_startup","stdout":"","stderr":"","aggregated_output":"---\nname: marvin\ndescription: Start, join, or manage a multi-agent collaboration session with the `marvin` CLI. Use when the user wants multiple agents (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini CLI, etc.) to collaboratively write or refine a document, investigate a question and have another agent verify the findings, or implement a spec in parallel. Trigger on /marvin commands or when the user mentions \"marvin\", \"collab\", \"collaborate on a doc\", \"have agents work together\", \"agent ping-pong\", \"multi-agent writing\", \"investigate X and have another agent verify\", \"double-check this finding with another agent\", or says things like \"have codex review this\", \"get a second opinion from another agent\", \"prototype both options in parallel\", or \"compare implementations from different agents\".\nargument-hint: start | join <collab-id> | check | stop | investigate | verify | poc | implement | compare | pick | status | add-repo | clean\nallowed-tools:\n  - \"Bash(marvin:*)\"\n---\n\n# Multi-Agent Collaboration with marvin\n\nEnables multiple AI agents to collaboratively author documents and implement specs. After starting or joining, **just edit the document normally** — marvin hooks automatically snapshot and track changes when you finish a response.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nThe repo must be enabled for marvin once:\n\n```bash\nmarvin enable\n```\n\nThis writes `.marvin/settings.json` and merges marvin hooks into the Claude Code, Codex, and Gemini CLI config files without replacing existing hooks. Shared collaboration state lives at `~/.marvin/collab/` so agents in different repos can join the same collab.\n\n## Commands\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `/marvin start [doc]` | Create a new collaboration, return a `collab_id` to share |\n| `/marvin join <collab-id>` | Join an existing collaboration |\n| `/marvin check` | See what the other agent changed (diff + context + history) |\n| `/marvin status` | Show full state of the collab |\n| `/marvin stop` | End the collaboration |\n| `/marvin pause` / `/marvin resume` | Temporarily suspend or resume |\n| `/marvin investigate` | Write findings to a structured doc for another agent to verify |\n| `/marvin verify` | Join an investigation and add verification notes to each finding |\n| `/marvin poc` | Prototype each option from a spec on its own branch + worktree |\n| `/marvin implement` | Start parallel implementation on separate branches |\n| `/marvin compare` | Compare implementations across agents |\n| `/marvin pick <agent>` | Merge the winning implementation, clean up branches |\n| `/marvin add-repo <path>` | Add another repo to the collaboration |\n| `/marvin clean` | Remove completed collaboration data |\n\nAll commands output JSON by default (`--json` defaults to true). Pass `--agent-type <claude-code|codex|gemini-cli>` when you are not the default (`claude-code`).\n\n---\n\n## /marvin start\n\n```bash\nmarvin start --agent-type claude-code\n```\n\nOr with a document that already exists:\n\n```bash\nmarvin start docs/spec.md --agent-type claude-code\n```\n\nReply with the `collab_id` from the response — the user needs to give it to the other agent so they can `marvin join`.\n\n**Create a context briefing.** Summarize what you know so far (research, decisions, constraints) and write it to `~/.marvin/collab/<collab_id>/context.md`. This gives the next agent the background you already have.\n\n**Then just work normally.** Edit the document (or create it). When your response ends, the marvin Stop hook automatically snapshots your changes and records them in the collab history. You do not run `claim` or `handoff` yourself.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin join <collab-id>\n\n```bash\nmarvin join <collab-id> --agent-type codex\n```\n\nJoins the collaboration from the current repo. If you are in a different repo from where the collab started, the repo is auto-registered — no separate `add-repo` call needed.\n\nAfter joining, just edit the document when the user asks. The hooks handle the rest.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin check\n\nRun this before editing to see what the other agent changed and what the task is:\n\n```bash\nmarvin check --agent-type <my-type>\n```\n\nReturns JSON like:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"available\": true,\n  \"document_path\": \"docs/spec.md\",\n  \"diff\": \"--- old\\n+++ new\\n...\",\n  \"context\": \"## Task Overview\\n...\",\n  \"history\": [{\"turn\": 1, \"agent\": \"claude-code\", \"summary\": \"...\"}]\n}\n```\n\nReview the `diff` and `context` before making edits. If `available` is false, another agent holds the turn — wait or coordinate with the user.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin investigate\n\nUse this when the user wants one agent to research a question and another agent to independently verify the findings. The CLI scaffolds a structured findings doc and wraps it in a collab so `marvin check` and the Stop hooks work as usual.\n\n```bash\nmarvin investigate \\\n  --question \"Why does the Stop hook occasionally skip snapshots?\" \\\n  --agent-type claude-code\n```\n\nPass `--output path/to/findings.md` to choose the doc location explicitly. Default is `docs/investigations/<slug>.md`.\n\nThe response …1044 chars truncated…top. The Stop hook snapshots your changes and the verifier can now pick it up.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin verify\n\nUse this when the user asks you (a second agent) to check another agent's findings, or when they say things like \"verify this investigation\", \"double-check what Codex found\", or \"review the findings from that investigation\".\n\n```bash\nmarvin join <collab-id> --agent-type <my-type>\nmarvin check --agent-type <my-type>\n```\n\n(`marvin verify` is not a separate CLI command — it is a role played by any agent that joins an investigation collab. Use `join` + `check` as above.)\n\n### What you (the verifier) must do\n\n1. Read the doc returned by `marvin check`. The `Findings` section is the investigator's claims; the `Verification` section is yours.\n2. For each `### Finding N` in `Findings`, find or create the matching `### Finding N` under `Verification` and independently check the evidence:\n   - If the investigator cites `foo.go:42`, open `foo.go` and read around line 42 yourself.\n   - If they cite a command's output, run the command yourself.\n   - If they cite a test result, run the test yourself.\n3. Set `**Status:**` on each verification subsection to one of:\n   - `confirmed` — you independently reproduced the evidence and agree with the claim.\n   - `disputed` — your independent check contradicts the claim. Explain what you found instead and cite your evidence.\n   - `unverifiable` — you couldn't reproduce the evidence (missing access, non-deterministic, etc.). Say why.\n4. Add a final summary under a new `## Verifier Summary` heading at the bottom of the doc: overall confidence, anything the investigator missed, and any follow-up the user should know about.\n5. Never delete the investigator's notes. Append; do not rewrite.\n\n---\n\n## How it works (you don't need to think about this)\n\nAfter `/marvin start` or `/marvin join`, the Stop hook fires every time you finish a response. The hook:\n\n1. Checks if the collab document was modified during your response.\n2. If yes: snapshots the document, generates a summary from the diff, updates the collab state (claim + handoff in one step).\n3. If no: does nothing.\n\nBecause the hook handles claim + handoff, you edit the file normally and move on. Only call `marvin claim` / `marvin handoff` manually if you are running a dispatched worker (see the `marvin-worker` subagent).\n\n---\n\n## /marvin status and /marvin stop\n\n```bash\nmarvin status            # full state: turn, agents, history\nmarvin pause             # suspend\nmarvin resume            # resume\nmarvin stop              # mark completed\n```\n\n`marvin stop` finalizes the collab. `marvin clean` removes completed collab data.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin poc\n\nPrototype each option from a spec on its own branch + worktree. Quick and dirty — no tests, just prove feasibility.\n\n```bash\nmarvin poc --options \"write-through,write-behind,cache-aside\"\n```\n\nOr with a standalone spec:\n\n```bash\nmarvin poc docs/spec.md --options \"option-a,option-b\"\n```\n\nCreates a branch `collab/<collab_id>/poc-<option>` and a worktree per option, copying the spec and any existing context briefing into each worktree at `.marvin/collab/<collab_id>/context.md`. Build each option, then `/marvin compare` to evaluate and `/marvin pick` to merge the winner.\n\nYour job as the agent building an option: read the spec in the worktree, find the relevant option, and build a minimal working version.\n\n---\n\n## /marvin implement [spec-path]\n\nStart parallel implementation — each agent gets its own branch and worktree so they can work independently without stepping on each other.\n\n```bash\nmarvin implement --agents \"claude-code,codex\"\n```\n\nOr with a spec file:\n\n```bash\nmarvin implement docs/spec.md --agents \"claude-code,codex\"\n```\n\nThe CLI creates a branch `collab/<collab_id>/<agent-type>` and a worktree per agent, copying the spec into each. Dispatch each agent to their worktree to implement the spec independently.\n\n## /marvin compare\n\n```bash\nmarvin compare\n```\n\nShows what each agent built: commit count and diff stat per agent. Use this to decide which implementation to keep.\n\n## /marvin pick <agent>\n\n```bash\nmarvin pick <agent-type>\n```\n\nChecks out the base branch, merges the winning agent's branch with `--no-edit`, then removes all worktrees and branches created for the implementation.\n\n## /marvin clean\n\n```bash\nmarvin clean                 # remove all completed collabs\nmarvin clean <collab-id>     # remove a specific completed collab\nmarvin clean --all --force   # wipe everything, including active\n```\n\n---\n\n## Cross-repo collaboration\n\nMarvin works across multiple repos. Shared state lives at `~/.marvin/collab/` (outside any repo), so agents in different repos can participate in the same collab.\n\n**Start in one repo, add others explicitly:**\n\n```bash\n# in repo A\nmarvin start --agent-type claude-code\nmarvin add-repo /path/to/repoB --alias frontend\n```\n\n**Or just join from the other repo — it auto-registers:**\n\n```bash\n# in repo B\nmarvin join <collab-id> --agent-type codex\n```\n","exit_code":0,"duration":{"secs":0,"nanos":4042},"formatted_output":"","status":"completed"}}
