iagram validation ok');\nNODE\n```\n\nExpected: FAIL because the README currently implies overview-level diagrams.\n\n**Step 3: Write minimal implementation**\n\nUpdate the `code-tour` summary in `README.md` so it says:\n- the initial overview is narrative\n- diagrams may be used in walkthrough follow-ups for specific targets when they clarify behavior\n\n**Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun the same Node script again.\n\nExpected: PASS\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add README.md\ngit commit -m \"Document drill-down diagram behavior in code-tour\"\n```\n\n### Task 3: Run final verification\n\n**Files:**\n- Verify: `skills/code-tour/SKILL.md`\n- Verify: `README.md`\n\n**Step 1: Run combined validation**\n\nRun:\n\n```bash\nnode - <<'NODE'\nconst fs = require('fs');\nconst skill = fs.readFileSync('skills/code-tour/SKILL.md', 'utf8');\nconst readme = fs.readFileSync('README.md', 'utf8');\nif (skill.includes('## Visual Map')) throw new Error('overview still contains Visual Map');\nif (!skill.includes('walkthrough follow-ups')) throw new Error('missing walkthrough-followup diagram guidance');\nif (!skill.includes('Do not draw repo tree or folder-layout diagrams')) throw new Error('missing default-diagram prohibition');\nif (!readme.includes('walkthrough follow-ups')) throw new Error('README missing walkthrough-followup wording');\nconsole.log('combined validation ok');\nNODE\ngit diff --check\ngit status --short\n```\n\nExpected:\n- validation prints `combined validation ok`\n- `git diff --check` prints nothing\n- `git status --short` shows only the intended modified files before committing, then nothing after the final commit\n\n**Step 2: Review the skill manually**\n\nConfirm that:\n- the initial overview template is text-only\n- drill-down prompts still invite concrete walkthroughs\n- diagram guidance now lives in the drill-down follow-up section\n\n**Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add skills/code-tour/SKILL.md README.md\ngit commit -m \"Refocus code-tour diagrams on walkthroughs\"\n```\n"},"/Users/alisha/.marvin/worktrees/project-overview/docs/plans/2026-04-29-code-tour-drilldown-diagrams-design.md":{"type":"add","content":"# Code Tour Drill-Down Diagrams Design\n\n## Summary\n\nRefocus `code-tour` so the initial overview is always text-first and never produces a generic repo-level diagram. Diagrams should be reserved for targeted follow-up walkthroughs such as `Walk me through skills/what-happened/SKILL.md`, where the subject is concrete and a visual explanation can clarify behavior, fallback paths, or decision flow.\n\n## Problem\n\nThe current design allows an overview-level `Visual Map` section. In this repo, that encourages the wrong abstraction: a folder-layout sketch of the repository. That kind of diagram is not useful for understanding how a specific skill works and does not answer the user’s actual follow-up questions.\n\n## Goals\n\n- Remove diagrams from the initial `code-tour` overview.\n- Keep the initial overview focused on narrative orientation: repo purpose, recent activity, hot files, contributors, and drill-down prompts.\n- Allow diagrams only during targeted walkthrough follow-ups, where the subject is explicit.\n- Prefer behavioral diagrams over folder or layout diagrams.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Producing directory-tree diagrams by default.\n- Drawing a repo-wide architecture map unless the user asks for a specific architecture explanation later.\n- Adding a second top-level mode or separate skill.\n\n## Proposed Behavior\n\n### Initial `code-tour` invocation\n\nThe first response remains text-only:\n\n- `## What this repo is`\n- `## Architecture at a glance`\n- `## Recent activity (last 30 days)`\n- `## Hot files & key contributors`\n- `## Want to drill in?`\n\nNo diagram section appears in the initial overview.\n\n### Follow-up walkthroughs\n\nWhen the user asks a concrete walkthrough question such as:\n\n- `Walk me through skills/what-happened/SKILL.md`\n- `Explain how search works in this repo`\n- `Show me the flow in session-handoff`\n\nthe skill may include a small diagram if it improves understanding.\n\n## Diagram Rules For Follow-Ups\n\n- Only draw diagrams when the walkthrough target is concrete: a file, skill, subsystem, or contributor thread.\n- Prefer diagrams that explain behavior:\n  - decision flow\n  - fallback flow\n  - input -> resolution -> output flow\n  - state or branching logic inside the target\n- Do not draw repo tree or folder-layout diagrams as the default walkthrough visual.\n- Use at most one diagram by default for a follow-up; use two only when the second explains a distinct behavior that the first cannot.\n- After each diagram, add 1-2 sentences explaining what to notice.\n\n## Evidence Threshold\n\nFollow-up diagrams are allowed only when they are grounded in:\n\n- the target file content\n- explicit command flow in the skill\n- clear fallback branches\n- explicit references in README or nearby files\n\nDo not infer behavior from path names alone.\n\n## Output Changes\n\nThe initial overview contract stays `Entire Code Tour:` but loses the `Visual Map` section entirely.\n\nThe drill-down section should explicitly say that diagrams may be used in walkthrough follow-ups when a concrete target is selected.\n\n## Files Expected To Change\n\n- `skills/code-tour/SKILL.md`\n- `README.md`\n\n## Validation\n\n- Confirm the overview template no longer contains `## Visual Map`.\n- Confirm the drill-down section mentions diagrams for targeted walkthroughs.\n- Confirm the README summary no longer implies overview-level diagrams.\n"}},"status":"completed"}}
