{"timestamp":"2026-04-29T23:52:15.322Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"It’s a high-level **GitHub webhook ingestion pipeline**.\n\nIn plain terms:\n\n- **Left side**: GitHub sends a webhook to your HTTP endpoint.\n- **Middle**: the raw webhook gets pushed onto a **Cloudflare Queue** so processing is async, durable, and retriable.\n- **Queue worker**: `processQueueMessage` is the queue consumer. It does idempotency on `deliveryId` and stores oversized payloads in KV.\n- **Dispatcher**: `processAllWebhookEvents(...)` is the fan-out point. It takes one incoming delivery and routes it to the right event handlers.\n\nThe lower branches are the handler groups:\n\n- `processWebhookEvent`: general repo/branch bookkeeping\n- `processInstallationEvent`: GitHub App install / uninstall / repo access changes\n- `processAccessChangeEvent`: membership / team / org access updates\n- `processPullRequestEvent`: PR indexing and sync\n- `processTrailMergeOnPRClose`, `processTrailLinkOnPROpened`, `processTrailGhPrIdLinkOnPROpened`: PR-related “trail” linkage / merge behaviors\n- `processSessionsPushEvent`: special handling for pushes to session/checkpoint refs\n- `processCommitPushEvent`: normal commit-push ingestion\n- `processTrailMergeDetection`: fallback merge detection from push events\n- `processTrailCIDraftPR`: shadow draft PR creation for CI\n- `handlePushAutoRuns`: push-triggered agent automation\n\nSo the main point of the diagram is:\n\n**one webhook comes in -> queue it -> dedupe/process safely -> dispatch to multiple domain-specific handlers depending on event type.**\n\nOne caution: those file/function labels do **not** exist in this repo, so I’m explaining the diagram from the labels you pasted rather than from local source. If you want, I can also turn this into:\n- a simpler 5-line explanation for docs, or\n- a “what each branch means” walkthrough for one specific branch like `processSessionsPushEvent` or the PR/trail flow.","phase":"fin